<subSubSection id="50DBD8E27B388D4CFF064796A13AF9AF" pageId="18" pageNumber="73" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="187E8B697B388D4CFF064796A308FA49" blockId="18.[189,310,1426,1452]" box="[189,310,1426,1452]" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">
<heading id="43363C057B388D4CFF064796A308FA49" bold="true" box="[189,310,1426,1452]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="73" reason="3">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B388D4CFF064796A308FA49" bold="true" box="[189,310,1426,1452]" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="187E8B697B388D4CFF0647C6A13AF9AF" blockId="18.[188,1400,1474,1611]" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">
This species has the terga densely punctate and is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B388D4CFC2947C7A622FA39" baseAuthorityName="Schrottky" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[914,1052,1475,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minarum">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B388D4CFC2947C7A19CFA38" box="[914,930,1475,1501]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B388D4CFC0947C7A622FA39" box="[946,1052,1475,1500]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">minarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in size (
<quantity id="DF39268C7B388D4CFB3D47C6A6F1FA38" box="[1158,1231,1474,1501]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="73" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
) and the rows of long (1.2 od) submarginal setae on S4 and S5. From this species it can be separated by the strigate vertex, the sparsely punctate mesoscutum disc (both punctate in 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B388D4CFC1F4408A610F9C0" baseAuthorityName="Schrottky" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[932,1070,1548,1574]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minarum">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B388D4CFC1F4408A188F9C3" box="[932,950,1548,1574]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B388D4CFC7F4408A610F9C0" box="[964,1070,1548,1573]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">minarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and by the shorter and less rugulose metapostnotum. Females are not known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="50DBD8E27B388D4CFF064470A3CAF8E2" pageId="18" pageNumber="73" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="187E8B697B388D4CFF064470A37AF96B" blockId="18.[189,324,1652,1678]" box="[189,324,1652,1678]" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">
<heading id="43363C057B388D4CFF064470A37AF96B" bold="true" box="[189,324,1652,1678]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="73" reason="3">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B388D4CFF064470A37AF96B" bold="true" box="[189,324,1652,1678]" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="187E8B697B388D4CFF0644A7A3CAF8E2" blockId="18.[188,1398,1699,1800]" pageId="18" pageNumber="73">Named after Jurupari, a South American god of darkness and evil, who visits people in their dreams with nightmares and presages, and preventing them from screaming by asphyxiation. The name is used as a proper noun in apposition.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
